The paper deals with coordination mechanisms and game theory in the context of scheduling jobs to machines, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.GT (Game Theory) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the efficiency of the outcomes of the induced game, which could also place it in the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The use of coordination mechanisms and scheduling policies could also suggest that the paper belongs to the cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) and cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) sub-categories. Finally, the mention of bounds on the price of anarchy and price of stability could place the paper in the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category.
